* * *
Aivar Tonso, Hea Uus Heli Festival, 2007:

&quot;It&amp;#039;s hard to objectively describe DJ Sigue Sigue Fabrique&amp;#039;s lively mashup dj sets. They tend to float out of the style and form boundaries, creating a frivolous void while playing with the terms &quot;clich&quot;, &quot;shift&quot;, &quot;error&quot; and &quot;deja-vu&quot;. Perfectly synched rhythm patterns let the listeners enjoy themselves, until they are deliberately &quot;shifted&quot; by error.
Playfulness + break + error + llektro + 8bit + glam = RoboDada
In addition to manipulating digital music files using dj software, he uses DIY style loops - often too much at a time - and vinyl records combined with Finalscratch.&quot;

He is also an active music producer under several aliases (actually creating non-existent bands with label mates using the moniker &quot;The Festival of Non-Existent Bands&quot;) and remixer, emphasizing the terms &quot;deconstruction&quot; and &quot;shift&quot; of pop music, for instance an underground cult hit/remix of ex-Soviet pop star Anne Veski&amp;#039;s track (titled &quot;Anne Pseudoveski - Aparaat&quot;) plus remixes for ska-pop-rock group &quot;Soterios&quot; (&quot;Twisted Romance Fabrique&amp;#039;s amiga_adult_riot rmx&quot;) and myspace band &quot;1-800-Zombie&quot; (to be released).
Founder of Robodada Records, conceptual record label living up to its name (www.robodada.com)

